Title: Architecture Diagram
Describe: Runtime boundaries include the CLI main thread, cron threads, teammate threads, background tool threads, the Anthropic API, and file-backed local state.
------------------------------------------------------------
[Example]
S04_ARCHITECTURE: Runtime boundaries

[Description]
This architecture is not a conventional multi-module layered system.

It is a teaching harness composed at runtime: the main CLI thread appends user input to `history`, `agent_loop` calls the Anthropic API, the model returns `tool_use` blocks, and local handlers execute them.

The cron scheduler discovers scheduled prompts, the cron autorun path drives the same agent loop, teammate threads run independent model loops, and background workers return delayed tool output.

[UML]
@startuml
left to right direction
actor "User CLI" as User
node "Main process" as Proc {
  component "__main__ input loop" as CLI
  component "agent_loop" as Loop
  component "cron_autorun_loop" as AutoCron
  component "cron_scheduler_loop" as Cron
  component "spawn_teammate_thread.run" as Teammate
  component "background worker" as Background
  component "HOOKS permission/logging" as Hooks
}
cloud "Anthropic Messages API" as API
database ".tasks\n.worktrees\n.mailboxes\n.transcripts\n.memory\n.scheduled_tasks.json" as Store
component "mock MCP servers\ndocs/deploy" as MCP
User -- CLI
CLI -- Loop
AutoCron -- Loop
Loop -- API
Loop -- Hooks
Loop -- Store
Loop -- MCP
Cron -- Store
Teammate -- API
Teammate -- Store
Background -- Store
MCP -- Loop
@enduml

[Detail]
Start from the CLI on the left.

Arrows show call, read/write, or event injection direction.

`agent_loop` is the core execution path for model tool calls; the cron autorun path also enters it through `agent_lock`.

The storage node represents local teaching stores rather than a database abstraction.

The main architectural risk is shared global and file-backed state across daemon threads.

Cron and background dictionaries use locks in places, but task files, mailbox files, and pending protocol requests are not protected by a complete transaction model.
